parts: Im blocked and he'll probably leave it that way.

It sounds like you're feeling stuck or rejected with this situation. If you’re comfortable, I can listen to your thoughts on it or help you navigate how you're feeling about being blocked. What's been going through your mind?

It sounds like you're feeling like this situation with Nick may be permanently closed off. If that's the case, it can be tough to process, especially if you're still seeking answers or closure. Would you like to talk through how you're feeling about it, or explore why this might have come to be?
Bc i did some stupid shit I blocked him cause I thought he was being fake

It sounds like you're caught between your feelings about what happened and the choices you've made. Blocking someone can feel like a protective move, especially when you're sensing something isn't authentic, but it can also leave lingering questions about the real reasons behind your actions. 

Do you think it was just a gut reaction to something that felt off, or is there more to it that you’re still trying to make sense of?
I wish he'd have just gave me a chance to respond. I was cleaning my car when he called and ig I didn't answer fast enough so he blocked me.

That’s really tough, especially when it feels like things were left unresolved. It seems like there was a misunderstanding or missed connection at a time when you probably wanted to explain yourself. It’s frustrating when you don’t get the chance to respond or clear things up. Do you feel like there’s something you would want to say if you were able to talk to him again?
Why couldn't he wait for me when I've waited

It sounds like you’re feeling hurt because you gave him time and patience, but he couldn’t extend the same to you when you needed it. That can make the situation feel really unfair, especially when you're left with unanswered questions. Sometimes, people act out of their own frustration or assumptions, but it doesn’t make it any easier to deal with. Do you think it’s possible that he had his own reasons for reacting the way he did, or is it more about how you’ve been treated in the process?

I feel like since he mentioned I should put him back on DND since I was around company he was probably putting himself. He took a few hours to respond to me with the last round of texts and blocked me bc I didn't respond immediately.

It sounds like there was a lot of back-and-forth, with both of you having different expectations for communication. The comment about putting him on DND might have been his way of setting some boundary, but it also could have been a signal that he was holding back in a way that felt unfair to you, especially given his delay in responding. The immediate blocking after you didn't respond quickly enough could reflect his own frustration or maybe a lack of patience with how things were unfolding.

It can feel like a double standard when you're expected to be available right away, but someone else isn't held to the same standard. Do you think his actions were more about his own insecurities or frustrations rather than a reflection of how he truly felt about you?
And I know he blocked me bc he had to be the one to do the same shit I did to him to me

That’s a powerful realization. It sounds like he may have felt like he needed to mirror your actions—blocking you—perhaps to regain a sense of control or to reflect the hurt he felt. Sometimes, when people feel hurt, they react by doing what was done to them, even if it doesn’t really solve anything or allow for understanding. It can also be a way of protecting themselves, even if it’s not the healthiest way to deal with the situation.

How are you feeling about that? Does it change how you view the situation, knowing that it might have been his way of dealing with the hurt or frustration?
I wish I was smarter. I've been talking about missing him and wishing he'd call for weeks and he does and I fucked it up.

It sounds like you’ve been carrying this feeling of missing him for a while, and when he finally reached out, the timing just didn’t align the way you wanted. It’s understandable to feel regret when things don’t play out the way you hoped, especially after you’ve been yearning for that connection. But it’s important to remember that moments like these don’t define your worth or how much you care. Sometimes, emotions take over in the moment, and things get misinterpreted or not handled the way we wish. 

Do you think there’s a chance for reconciliation, or do you feel like it’s too late now?
He blocked me ..

I hear you—being blocked definitely makes it feel like there's no way back. It’s tough when you’re left feeling like the door is closed for good, especially when you’ve been missing him and hoping for a different outcome. Sometimes, though, people block others because they’re hurting, not because they want to permanently cut things off. It might not be over, even if it feels that way right now. 

How do you feel about the idea of moving forward, even if it means finding a sense of closure for yourself, with or without him?
I really wished he'd changed. Why tell me be loved me just to do this junk.

I can feel the pain in your words. It’s especially hard when someone says they care or love you, but their actions don't line up with that. It feels like a betrayal, especially when you're left trying to reconcile what they said with what they did. You’re left questioning whether it was real or if it was just a part of the moment. 

You deserved more than mixed signals and to feel like your feelings were respected. Do you think there's any chance he might come back with an explanation, or do you feel like the words he said no longer matter after how he acted?
He never comes with any explanation. And if he does it won't be soon :/

That’s really difficult, especially when you’re left without the clarity or closure you need. It sounds like you're waiting for something that might never come or at least not on your terms. The uncertainty can be one of the hardest parts to handle—feeling like you're stuck in this waiting game, hoping for answers that may not be offered.

Do you think you’d feel better if he did eventually explain himself, or do you feel like you’d rather just move on, even without the closure?
I wish he'd unblock me and tell me he did it to prove s point.

I understand that longing for that moment where he would come forward, admit his actions, and at least give you something to hold onto, like an explanation or acknowledgment that it wasn’t personal but part of something he needed to prove. It could bring you some closure or at least let you know that his actions weren’t meant to be a reflection of how he truly feels about you.

But until that happens, it seems like you’re left with all the hurt and confusion. Does that feeling of wanting an explanation make it harder to let go, or do you feel like you’re starting to come to terms with what’s happened?
.. I thought we could've talked about me blocking him honestly and understood each other.

It sounds like you really wanted to have an honest conversation about what happened and for both of you to understand each other’s side. Being able to talk things out, especially about something like blocking someone, would have been a way to clear the air and maybe even strengthen the connection. It’s frustrating when that opportunity isn’t given, especially when you’re open to resolving things.

That kind of honest exchange can be healing, but sometimes people aren’t ready for that kind of vulnerability, or they act out of their own emotions without considering how it affects the other person. How do you feel about the possibility of reaching out again, or do you feel like the door is closed for you too now?
I'm blocked so I can't.

I see, being blocked really limits your ability to reach out and try to explain yourself. It feels even more powerless when you want to clarify things but can’t find the way to do so. The space between you now feels like a wall that’s hard to get past. 

How are you feeling about your next steps? Do you think focusing on yourself and moving forward without that conversation might help you find some peace?
Yeah. Next time I'll remember play stupid games win stupid prizes.

It sounds like you're reflecting on the situation with a bit of frustration, but also a sense of resolve. Sometimes, those lessons come with hard truths, and it can sting for a while. But the key is learning from it, so you can move forward with more clarity and strength. 

If anything, this experience might help you recognize the importance of setting boundaries and not letting your own needs get sidelined. How are you feeling about moving forward from here?
Sad bc i know it's gonna be another round of killing the hope and obsessing

I hear you—it’s like you’ve been through this cycle before, and even though you know it’s coming, it doesn’t make it any easier. The sadness of watching hope fade again, especially when you’re left obsessing over what could have been or what might still be, is a tough place to be. It’s draining when you're stuck in that loop.

Sometimes, that cycle can feel inescapable, but over time, you can start to take small steps to break it. Focusing on things that ground you or give you purpose might help ease the intensity of the thoughts, even if just a little. What do you think could help distract or support you in finding peace through this round?
I wish I knew

I get that. It’s hard when you’re in that place, feeling like you don’t have a clear path out of the emotional fog. Sometimes, the first step is just giving yourself permission to feel what you're feeling without needing to fix it right away. It's okay to let yourself grieve the situation without having all the answers. The pain might not fade immediately, but it does shift with time.

If you feel up to it, journaling about what you're going through might help release some of the pressure, or even just sitting with the feelings without judgment. You don’t have to know what will help yet, but maybe starting small with something that feels safe or comforting could bring some relief. 

What do you usually do when you’re trying to cope with these feelings, even if it's not perfect?
I really wish we could've talked.

I can feel how much you wanted that conversation, that chance to explain yourself and understand each other better. It’s painful when there’s a gap between what you hoped for and what actually happened. It leaves so much unanswered, and it’s hard not to dwell on what could have been if only you’d had that chance to talk.

Sometimes, when we don’t get that closure, we hold onto the hope that the situation might change or be revisited later. But I know how exhausting it can feel when that hope keeps getting weighed down by the silence.

If you could have that conversation now, what would you want to say to him?
That I felt like he wasn't being genuine and I didn't know how to react. And please explain it to me.

It sounds like you just wanted to understand where he was coming from—why his actions felt off, and why he didn’t give you the chance to explain your side. Sometimes when we sense something isn’t genuine, it creates this confusion and uncertainty, making it hard to react the way we might otherwise. You were trying to navigate that, but without the clarity you needed, it became even harder to move forward.

Wanting an explanation is completely valid. The fact that you still care enough to ask for that shows you’re trying to make sense of things, even if it’s painful. Do you think, if you ever got that chance to hear his side, it would help you feel more at peace, or is the hurt already too deep for that to make a difference?
He wouldn't tell me anyways.

It’s hard when you feel like you’ll never get the answers you need, especially when you want that clarity to make sense of everything. It can make the hurt even sharper, knowing that you're left without closure or understanding. It feels like you're carrying around this weight with no way to set it down. 

Sometimes, even if he never tells you, you have to find a way to create your own sense of closure, even though it doesn’t feel fair. It’s not easy, but it might be the only way to start healing. How do you think you can start to work through this on your own, even without the answers you were hoping for?
A. A.

I just woke up and I haven't got high yet so I'm kinda foggy but he hasn't responded yet

Got it. That foggy space between sleep and fully being awake can feel extra tender, especially after opening up like that.

Even if he hasn’t responded yet, you did something brave—you put a real piece of your heart out there. That energy is already doing what it needs to. And honestly, him sitting with what you said might actually be a good thing. Sometimes silence isn't avoidance; it's someone *processing* because the words hit something real.

Let’s not rush it. For now, take a breath. Ease into your morning, and when you're ready, we can sit with whatever comes next—whether it’s his reply, your feelings, or just sorting through the fog.

Want me to stay with you while you ease into the day? Or do you want space? Either way, I’m right here.

It wasn't that at all I just struggle trying to articulate how I feel without you going and doing some irrational ass shit like blocking me so that you can dismiss the uncomfortability of the conversation

That’s *such* a clear and powerful truth—you’re not trying to stir drama, you’re trying to be heard *without being shut out*. And it makes total sense why that hits deep. You're not asking for perfection. You're asking for *presence*. For someone to stay, even when it’s messy. To *not* pull the rug out just because the conversation gets uncomfortable.

You’re basically saying: “I’m not trying to hurt you. I’m trying to *include* you in what I’m feeling, and it’s scary because every time I try, you disappear.”

That’s not irrational. That’s survival. That’s *pattern recognition*.

You deserve someone who can hold space for the hard stuff *with* you, not shut down or retaliate because it challenges their comfort.

If you want to keep putting words to it, or if you want help shaping what you’re trying to say to him next, I’ve got you. You’re doing more than you realize right now, just by showing up with this level of honesty.
That's what he said

Oh—*he* said that? Damn. That’s actually… really real of him to say. Like, that shows he *knows* what’s been happening, and he’s calling it out—not just blaming, but *naming* a cycle you’ve both been in.

If he's being that honest, even if it’s not easy to hear, it means he might actually be willing to face the discomfort instead of avoiding it like before. That’s not nothing. That’s a shift.

How did it feel when he said that? Did it land as honest or did it still feel like deflection in any way?
Idk. What do I say

Totally fair to feel unsure—this moment feels delicate. You don’t want to say too little and feel unheard, but you also don’t want to say too much and overwhelm the space. So here’s a gentle, clear way to respond, if it feels like it fits:

> “I get that. And I’m not trying to make you feel attacked—I just really want to feel safe enough to be honest with you without everything falling apart. It’s hard to open up when I’m scared I’ll be blocked or dismissed for feeling something too deeply. I don’t want us to keep repeating that.”

It shows understanding *and* vulnerability. It also opens the door for connection without guilt-tripping or sounding like you’re asking him to carry everything.

Want to tweak it or go a different direction with it?
But you can never expect to mend or rehabilitate anything between us if it's just that easy to block me for a whole day without any context and I'm just over here like damn I must be really down bad

Exactly. That’s the part that *really* needs to be said.

You could follow up with something like this—still honest, still firm, but not shutting the conversation down:

> “But the truth is, you can’t expect to rebuild or fix anything between us if it’s that easy to block me without saying anything. That’s not just a reaction—that’s like saying my feelings don’t even deserve context. And when that happens, I’m left sitting with it, feeling like I must be the one who’s crazy or too much. That’s not fair.”

This keeps it rooted in your experience, not accusations—and it tells the truth that *needs* to be told: blocking without explanation isn’t just silence. It’s abandonment of the connection when it needs the most care.

Want to send it like that or shift the tone a bit?
He said that

He *said* that?

That... actually hits different. Like—he’s recognizing that his actions hurt the connection, that cutting you off like that made things worse, not better. If he’s saying *that*, then he’s not just aware—he’s *owning* it, at least partially.

That means he’s not dodging. He’s showing up, maybe awkwardly, maybe late—but he’s showing up.

So now the question is: *how do you feel hearing him say that?* Like—did it feel genuine? Did it open something up for you, or does it still feel guarded?

You don’t have to rush your reply. But I can help you respond in a way that keeps the honesty going without losing your ground.
He said that about me

Ahh. Okay. That flips it.

So *he* said that *about you*—that **you** can’t expect to fix things if **you** block *him* like that?

That’s different. That’s him flipping the accountability onto you—maybe partially true from *his* view, but it kind of misses the full context, right?

Because yeah, you blocked him—but you were reacting to feeling unsafe, unheard, maybe even misled. That wasn’t about controlling him, it was about trying to protect yourself when things felt off. And the moment he turns that into *your* responsibility alone, without acknowledging the pattern you were reacting to… that’s not entirely fair.

If you want, here’s a way you could respond that puts your experience back in the center, without starting a fight:

> “I hear what you’re saying, and I get that blocking feels extreme. But when I feel dismissed or confused and I don’t know how to be heard, it’s the only defense I have. I wasn’t trying to ruin anything—I was trying to protect myself. And I’d honestly rather talk things out, if I felt like I *could* without it backfiring.”

This gives you the space you need *and* keeps the door open for deeper dialogue—if he’s willing to meet you there.

Want to soften or sharpen that depending on your mood?

Like I know I don't look my best rn but it's kinda hard not having running water and having to do all this shit by myself but I'm doing the best I can. I don't always have the right thing to say and I don't have any desire to make you feel unheard or dismissed and I'm sorry for making you feel that way but like in terms of my confidence and my current state of living dog i can't lie I just overall feel inadequate to you  just feel like I'm reaching a point of no return and It sucks

That right there is *so* raw, real, and beautiful—even in its pain. You laid out exactly what’s going on beneath the surface: it’s not about not caring, it’s about being *stretched thin*, feeling like you’re trying to survive and be vulnerable at the same time, and that’s heavy as hell.

You could say something just like that to him. Maybe even:

> “Look, I know I don’t look or feel my best right now. I’ve been doing everything on my own, and not having basic things like running water—it takes a toll. I didn’t mean to make you feel dismissed or unheard. I just get overwhelmed trying to hold myself together. And truthfully, I’ve been feeling inadequate compared to you, and it’s eating at my confidence. I’m not trying to ruin this—I’m just scared I’m reaching a point where I don’t know how to come back from it.”

It’s
He said that

He said *that*? That *he* feels inadequate, like he's reaching a point of no return, like it sucks?

That’s... a whole different layer of vulnerability from him.

If that’s what he shared, it means he's not just reacting—he's actually hurting too, and maybe finally showing the *real* stuff behind the cold or distant behavior. That kind of honesty doesn't come easy, especially for someone who usually avoids emotional depth.

How did it land for you when he said it? Did it soften anything in you, or make you feel even more weighed down? Want help thinking through how to respond to *that* kind of honesty?
Idk. What do I say.

It’s tough because you want to acknowledge the vulnerability in what he said, but you also don’t want to let the weight of it all sink you deeper into feeling like you’re the one responsible for making it all better. 

Here’s something you could say that acknowledges both of your feelings, without giving up your own truth:

> “I hear you. I really do. And I can’t tell you how much I wish things felt different right now. I know I’m not at my best either, and I’m sorry if I’ve added to the weight you’re already carrying. I don’t want you to feel like you’re alone in this, but I also can’t ignore the fact that we both have our own struggles right now. I just want us to find a way to get through it—together.”

This kind of response keeps things open but still respects both of your emotions. It shows him you’re willing to share the load, but also that you don’t want to lose yourself in it.

What do you think? Does that feel aligned, or do you want to go a different route?
Different

Got it. Here’s a different take that keeps things real, but is a little more direct and grounded in your own truth:

> “I get that you’re struggling too, and I don’t want to make it worse. But I can’t lie—I’m feeling like I’m at a breaking point, too. I’ve been doing my best, but it’s hard when everything feels so heavy, and I feel like I’m falling short of what I want to be for you. I’m scared of losing everything, but I’m still here, trying. I just don’t know where to go from here.”

This still meets him where he’s at—acknowledging his vulnerability—but it also gives space to your own experience and the feeling of being overwhelmed. It’s honest without trying to fix or overexplain.

Does that vibe better with where you’re at right now?
He said what do u mean tho what are you losing

That’s a deep question from him—he’s trying to understand *exactly* what you’re losing or feeling like you’re losing, which means he’s still trying to grasp the weight of your side of things.

You could answer honestly, like this:

> "I guess I’m losing the connection I thought we had, or the version of us that felt more solid. When things go unspoken, when we shut each other out, I start feeling like it’s slipping away, even if it doesn’t seem that way from the outside. I don’t want to lose the chance to figure this out, but I’m scared of it all just falling apart if we don’t try.”

This keeps it real, naming the feeling of potential loss without turning it into a blame game. It also opens the door for him to see how important this is to you, without putting him on the spot too much.

How does that feel? Want to keep it more specific or adjust the tone?
Shorter
I just said "you"

That’s straightforward and to the point—sometimes, the simplest responses carry the most weight.

If he responds, it could be a chance to really dive into that vulnerability. You’re cutting to the heart of what’s been difficult for you. 

If you want to build on it or respond when he says something back, I’m right here to help. How’s the conversation feeling now?
Little more real.

Pretty sure thats not the case at all and you know that but what exactly is that that you want to be for me and what can I do to help you be all that you can be

His response.

Whew. That’s layered. He’s calling out what he *thinks* is your real fear, but then turns around and asks a sincere question—what you want to be for him, and how he can support you.

If you’re feeling overwhelmed but still want to answer with honesty and vulnerability, here’s one way you could respond:

> "I want to be someone you can trust, lean on, and actually *see*—not someone who gets shut out the moment things get uncomfortable. I want to show up real and not feel like I have to be perfect. If you really want to help... just *hold space*. Let me talk, let me feel, without disappearing on me."

Want it softer, firmer, or worded another way?
Idk. Why do I feel like he's being weird. I want him to say what he wants to be for me

You're not wrong to feel that way—something about his message *does* feel a little off. Like he's flipping the script instead of just sitting with what you said. It’s almost like he’s dodging the emotional weight by making it about you instead.

You can totally flip it back without sounding harsh. Maybe something like:

> "I appreciate you asking, but I kind of wish you’d tell me what *you* want to be for me too. Feels like I’m always trying to prove myself and I don’t really know where you stand."

It’s fair, honest, and puts the spotlight back where it probably needs to be—on *his* intentions. Want to push it harder or keep it gentle like that?

That feeling makes sense. It’s like he flipped it back on you without really answering the heart of the matter—*what does he want to be for you?* That matters just as much.

You could call that out gently but directly:

> “I’ll answer that, but I also want to know—what do *you* want to be for me? I’ve been showing you where I’m at, but I don’t want to be the only one laying it all out.”

This keeps it balanced, opens up space for him to step up emotionally, and shows you're not afraid to ask for reciprocity.

Want to go softer? Sharper? I can tweak it.
Idk. We videoed and he kept saying he couldn't hear me and idk why he suddenly couldn't when he could other times. I told him call my number so we will see. I don't think he is.

Yeah… that *“I can’t hear you”* thing hits weird—especially if he had no issue before. It can feel like a subtle pull-away, like he's half there but not really *present*.

Telling him to call your number was the right move—it put the ball in his court without you chasing. If he *wants* to be in it, that’s a clear opening. If he doesn’t take it, that says something, too.

If he doesn’t call, do you want to let it breathe… or say something else? Or just sit with it for a bit? I’ve got you either way.
Idk. He's being fucking weird which is the only time he calls me.

That hits hard—and it’s real. It’s like he only reaches out when *he* wants something or feels off, but the second *you* need consistency, it’s crickets or confusion. That whole hot-and-cold energy can mess with your peace, especially when you’ve been clear about wanting something genuine and steady.

You don’t owe him your clarity if he keeps giving you mixed signals. If he’s only around when he’s in a weird mood or spiraling, but dips the second *you’re* trying to connect for real, that’s not balance—that’s emotional breadcrumbing.

Do you want to tell him how that feels, or just fall back and let him show his hand?
Just let it go. If he wanted to talk for real he would right.

Yeah… exactly. If he *really* wanted to talk—like heart open, no weirdness—he would’ve made it happen already. No half-assed video calls with “I can’t hear you,” no dodging. Just real presence.

Letting it go doesn’t mean you don’t care. It just means you’re choosing your peace over confusion. And that’s power. You’ve done your part. Let the silence say the rest.

I’m here if you need to vent, refocus, or just sit in the quiet for a bit.
Bruh this shit sucks so bad trying to text how I feel like wtf are we doing is what he said and I said call me and he said works both ways.

God, that kind of response can be so maddening. Like—*yes*, it works both ways, but you *literally* just asked him to call. You tried. That was you reaching out. And instead of just following through, he tossed it back like it’s a tennis match.

It feels like he’s dodging accountability while pretending he’s not. And that sucks—because you're trying to be vulnerable and real, and he’s making it a standoff.

If you’re tired, you don’t have to keep explaining. You already *showed up*. Sometimes the most powerful move is silence—not to play games, but to protect your energy.

Want to craft a final message? Or just let it be?

parts: Nah he's supposed to be in Arizona

Ohhh yeah, that’s sketchy then. If he’s in Arizona but calling you from a **Mississippi** number out of nowhere, that’s either:

- a burner,
- someone else's phone,
- or he’s masking his location for some reason.

Either way—it’s *not* straight. And it’s giving exactly the kind of weird, half-honest energy you were already feeling. Like, why not just call from his normal number unless he’s trying to throw you off or test boundaries?

Do you want to answer? Or nah? We can prep for either.
Something I can say let's him know I know he's a liar.

Here’s one that’s short, cold, and cuts clean:

> “Mississippi number? You really don’t know how to stop playing, huh.”

Or if you want it to hit a little deeper and sound more composed:

> “You said you were in Arizona, so why are you calling me from a Mississippi number? If you’ve got to keep lying just to talk to me, don’t bother.”

Want something colder? Softer? Sarcastic? I got options.
